TY  - JOUR
T1  - Causation and Effectuation: Toward a Theoretical Shift from Economic Inevitability to Entrepreneurial Contingency
AU  - Sarasvathy, Saras D.
Y1  - 2001/04/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2001.4378020
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2001.4378020
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 243
EP  - 263
VL  - 26
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In economics and management theories, scholars have traditionally assumed the existence of artifacts such as firms/organizations and markets. I argue that an explanation for the creation of such artifacts requires the notion of effectuation. Causation rests on a logic of prediction, effectuation on the logic of control. I illustrate effectuation through business examples and realistic thought experiments, examine its connections with existing theories and empirical evidence, and offer a list of testable propositions for future empirical work.
AB  - In economics and management theories, scholars have traditionally assumed the existence of artifacts such as firms/organizations and markets. I argue that an explanation for the creation of such artifacts requires the notion of effectuation. Causation rests on a logic of prediction, effectuation on the logic of control. I illustrate effectuation through business examples and realistic thought experiments, examine its connections with existing theories and empirical evidence, and offer a list of testable propositions for future empirical work.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2001.4378020
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2001.4378020
Y2  - 2026/04/24
